05292nam a22010695i 9780228009771DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280097717 a10.1515/97802280097712doi  a(DE-B1597)657255  a(OCoLC)1264414888  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHT241b.L36 2022 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a307.762231 aLang, Ursula, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiving with Yards :bNegotiating Nature and the Habits of Home /cUrsula Lang. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b67 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- tIntroduction -- tBuilding Urban Habitats -- tRhythms Of Inhabitation -- tChasing Yard Affects -- tPractising Property and Life in Common -- tConclusions -- tAcknowledgments -- tFigures -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aYards are not quite wild, yet rarely tamed. Across diverse residential landscapes in North America and beyond, yards are regulated by the state and markets, defined by imaginary property lines on maps, and sometimes central to privilege and exclusion.As urban life is reimagined for greater sustainability, resilience, and adaptation, Living with Yards invites readers to more fully engage with the possibilities of how we can coexist with our urban habitats. Ursula Lang uses the yard as a faceted lens through which to examine the multiple and contradictory ways people live in urban environments, and how perceptions of those environments are shaped by contemporary environmental policies and projects. Visual ethnography and narrative illustrate how inhabitants of Minneapolis live with their yards as sites of social and environmental care while also negotiating difference. Throughout, Lang’s subjects engage in diverse and creative everyday practices of cultivation and property ownership, often quite distinct from the environmental policies and projects in place.The process of reimagining cities as more sustainable and equitable must include knowledge of how people live within urban spaces. By conducting in-depth visits to more than forty yards and sharing her results, Lang provokes us to think about what else these realms of daily life might become. Living with Yards chronicles the interplay between the yard as habitat and our inhabitation of it, exploring the changes and innovations a better understanding of urban living might spark.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity and town life. 0aLawnsxSocial aspects. 0aLawns. 0aSociology, Urban. 0aUrban ecological design. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aGreat Migration.  aHenri Lefebvre.  aKathleen Stewart.  aMidwest.  aMinneapolis.  aaffect.  abackyard.  aclimate change.  acommoning.  acommons.  acultivation.  adaily life.  aemotional geography.  aenvironmental justice.  aethnography.  aeveryday life.  afront yard.  agarden.  ahabitat.  ahome grounds.  ahousing.  ainhabitation.  ainterview.  alandscape.  alawn.  amanagement.  anative.  aphenomenology.  aplace-based research.  aproperty.  aqualitative.  aracism.  arain.  aredlining.  aresidential.  aresilience.  astormwater.  asustainability.  aurban.  avisual.  awatershed.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2022z978311127419540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022800977140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9